                   mas angular resolution. The continuum emission is
                   highly elongated and is consistent with that expected
                   from a nearly edge-on disk. The high brightness and
                   lack of strong molecular lines from Orion I can be
                   used to argue against emission from dust. Collisional
                   ionization and H- free-free opacity, as in Mira
                   variables, require a central star with >~105 Lsolar,
                   which is greater than infrared observations allow.
                   However, if significant local heating associated with
                   accretion occurs, lower total luminosities are
                   possible. Alternatively, photoionization from an
                   early B-type star and p+/e- bremsstrahlung can
                   explain our observations, and Orion I may be an
